<!-- METHODOLOGY -->
<div class="page" id="page-methodology">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">The SIPM Framework</div>
    <div class="methodology-content">
      <p><strong>The Social Inflection Point Monitor</strong> is a framework for reading when movements are ready to tip — and positioning campaigns at those moments.</p>
      
      <h3>The Five Conditions for Tipping</h3>
      <p>Research into past movement inflection points consistently surfaces five conditions. A movement rarely tips on fewer than four. When all five are present, a trigger event ignites a cultural shift.</p>
      
      <div class="condition-grid">
        <div class="condition-card">
          <div class="num">1</div>
          <div class="name">Grievance Saturation</div>
        </div>
        <div class="condition-card">
          <div class="num">2</div>
          <div class="name">Narrative Availability</div>
        </div>
        <div class="condition-card">
          <div class="num">3</div>
          <div class="name">Infrastructure</div>
        </div>
        <div class="condition-card">
          <div class="num">4</div>
          <div class="name">Permission Structure</div>
        </div>
        <div class="condition-card">
          <div class="num">5</div>
          <div class="name">Trigger Potential</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <h3>Condition Definitions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Grievance Saturation (0-5):</strong> Not just grievance presence — saturation. The harm has accumulated enough that a significant portion feels it personally or viscerally.</li>
        <li><strong>Narrative Availability (0-5):</strong> The explanatory story exists and is accessible — who caused this, who suffers, and what can be done.</li>
        <li><strong>Organizational Infrastructure (0-5):</strong> Networks of people capable of activating are already connected. You can't build this during a crisis.</li>
        <li><strong>Permission Structure (0-5):</strong> The cultural/political environment endorses the movement's values or has become fragile enough to challenge.</li>
        <li><strong>Trigger Event Potential (0-5):</strong> Specific, emotionally legible incidents that prove the grievance is happening right now, to real people.</li>
      </ul>
      
      <h3>Outcome Scoring</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>5 – Full Change:</strong> Durable policy/institutional change achieved and maintained</li>
        <li><strong>4 – Major Win:</strong> Significant policy wins but vulnerable to reversal or incomplete</li>
        <li><strong>3 – Cultural Shift:</strong> Permanent change in public consciousness, discourse, or norms</li>
        <li><strong>2 – Partial Win:</strong> Some concessions extracted but core grievance unaddressed</li>
        <li><strong>1 – Awareness Only:</strong> Public attention generated without structural change</li>
        <li><strong>0 – Suppressed:</strong> Movement crushed with no lasting impact</li>
      </ul>
      
      <h3>Key Insight</h3>
      <p>The trigger doesn't create the conditions — the conditions determine when the trigger ignites. Build conditions relentlessly; be ready to amplify when the trigger comes.</p>
      
      <h3>Data Sources</h3>
      <p>This dashboard synthesizes research from academic literature on social movements, historical case analysis, and real-time tracking of active campaigns. 100 cases spanning 1977-2025 across all continents.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

